15/ Conclusion:
At the end of the day, that is basically all there is to it. The reasons why floors do not increase is because there are enough players that want to sell or do not perceive the project as worthwhile.  Collectively changing this on both ends will change price.

14/ cont.
This is why you typically need both of these - higher demand and less supply. Just raising the floor in the community doesn't mean anyone outside of it will want it (theoretically).

13/ Full Circle:
This is where economics comes back into play. Holding is just like decreasing the supply, and strong brand awareness is a way to increase demand.  When both supply decreases and demand increases, price drastically increases. BOOM. Example: BAYC.

12/ cont. 
#HODL accompanied with strong brand awareness is probably the best way to increase the floor price of an NFT project, but it has to be done collectively.  More people unwilling to sell their NFT and outsiders wanting the NFT will increase price!

11/ cont.
Just by collectively raising the floor does not mean there will be buyers at that price. It could result in less volume. Less volume = less liquidity, less liquidity = harder to sell your NFT. see the next 3 tweets ğŸ‘‡

10/ Considerations:
As stated, the owners determine the price floor. This is one of the reasons why community is so impactful in the NFT space.  The owners determine the price. A great community will build the project up.  Owners that donâ€™t care wonâ€™t.

9/ Example:
This is @fishyfamNFT 7-day volume. As you can see it has been decreasing over the past week. (I love the project and the art so I donâ€™t really care about this, but to new investors, this wouldnâ€™t look great) https://t.co/tfV2p0dsAn

8/ cont. 
Although this is not the end all be all indicator, it is something to look for.  You can track the volume traded on @LooksRareNFT or @opensea by clicking the tab â€œActivityâ€ next to the items.

7/ Volume:
This is why the amount traded is always an indicator of how a project is doing.  If not many NFTs in the project are getting sold, more are bound to get listed both decreasing the perceived value and liquidity.

6/ Lowering the Price Floor:
This typically happens when more NFTs are getting listed than sold. Investors who want to pull their money out will sell their NFT at or below the floor just to sell it.  It results in decreased perceived value of the project and lowering the floor.

5/ Raising the Price Floor:
The above is how you organically raise a price floor. The more NFTs being sold than being listed the higher the floor price should go â€“ increasing perceived value. This can also be done by all members of the community listing the NFT for a higher price

4/ cont. 
For @fishyfamNFT, out of all the owners, the lowest an  owners is willing to sell their NFT for is .2 $ETH.  If this owner delisted or sold the NFT, then the price floor would move up to the next lowest priced NFT in the project.  In this case: .204 $ETH.

3/ Example:
Letâ€™s take 2 extremes: @BoredApeYC and my current favorite @fishyfamNFT 
The current â€œprice floorâ€ is 94 $ETH and .2 $ETH respectively. 
All this really means is that out of all the owners of BAYC the lowest single owner is willing to sell their NFT for is 94 $ETH

2/ Floor Price in NFTs:
Since there are no laws to determine the minimum price projects/investors can sell their NFT for, Floor Prices work a little differently.  It is not 1 governing body that determines the minimum price, but the owners perceived value of the NFT.

1/ Floor Price in Economics:
Typically, there are laws in place that do not allow certain commodities or goods to fall below a certain price â€“ this would be considered the price floor.  Price floors determined by law have impacts on Supply and Demand.

So I think there is some misunderstanding or lack of knowledge for some on how #floorprice work. I know when I first got into #NFTs I had no clue. 

I am going to explain everything about floor prices and the valuation of NFTs in this ğŸ§µğŸ§µ

13/ Conclusion:
Aside from NFTs, there can be tax benefits to running a business. Typically most creators will have formed a business entity and the tax owed will flow similarly to how I described it. It isnâ€™t very complicated, and most creators have probably considered this.

12/ cont.
Code section 6017 states you must report self-employment income if you make over $400. For most freelancers in the NFT space I would imagine this applies.  The method of calculating the tax is not very different from above. There are some things to look out for though.

11/ The Freelancer: 
The freelancer is typically subject to the self-employment tax which flows similarly to owning an actual business.  There are additional taxes they may encounter different from a typically salaried employee, however.

10/ The Flow:
The above will typically all flow to schedule C which you will attach to your 1040.  This schedule will cover many of the common revenue and expense items you may encounter. Speak with your professional tax advisor if you are unsure.

9/ The Bottom Line:
That net income figure is what will go into your 1040 (individual tax return) and flow through and get taxed on. (Unless the creator decided to form a corporation instead of a flow through entity *that is getting too advanced*) (message me if this is you!)

8/ Example of an NFT Creator Business:
Sales of NFTs (before taxes in Oct)
Less: advertising expenses (Sept)
Less: running a website expense 
= net income (this is the figure that will get taxed)

7/ cont.
Now not all these expenses can get run through a business and receive those pretax deductions, but typically internet and other things that are used in your trade or business can qualify for those business deductions. The principle behind it is what matters. Back to NFTs

6/ cont.
$50,000 in sales at a 20% tax rate but this is business income that you can directly deduct expenses from! 50k â€“ 10k of expenses = 40k x 20% tax = 8k of tax owed meaning you are left with 32k an extra 2k dollars just because you own a business!
